WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:04.560
<v Teacher>How would you say to ventilate?

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:05.600
<v Student>Ventilar?

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:07.680
<v Teacher>Yeah, ventilacion ventilar.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:09.520
<v Teacher>How would you say to separate

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:12.260
<v Student>Separar.

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:12.820
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:12.820 --> 00:00:13.860
<v Teacher>Separar.

00:00:13.860 --> 00:00:19.780
<v Teacher>So in English what we pronounce is separate maybe like an E sound, but if you look at how it's written, it's an A.

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:20.660
<v Teacher>Separar.

00:00:20.660 --> 00:00:21.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:28.760
<v Teacher>So uh how was to know something to do with savi saver

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:31.740
<v Teacher>Sabel with a B.

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:34.380
<v Teacher>Another way to remember this is Homo sapien.

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:35.740
<v Teacher>There's that connection there.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:41.580
<v Teacher>The Homo sapien is the wise creature, supposedly.

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:43.740
<v Teacher>And and how was to come?

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:46.860
<v Teacher>Convenient.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:47.660
<v Teacher>Venir.

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:48.380
<v Teacher>Venir.

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:48.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:48.780 --> 00:00:51.500
<v Teacher>So we can remember that convenient is with coming.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.220
<v Teacher>When things come together, they are convenient.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:01:02.120
<v Teacher>We've seen the two forms of the verb end in R and the I form most of the time ends in O.

00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:05.320
<v Teacher>For example, I want, how was that?

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:06.940
<v Student>Quiero.

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:07.500
<v Teacher>Quiero.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.700
<v Teacher>I owe, which we can use like must.

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:11.260
<v Student>Debo.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:12.460
<v Teacher>Debo.

00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:14.460
<v Teacher>I try.

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:16.500
<v Teacher>Intento.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:17.540
<v Teacher>Intento.

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:24.420
<v Teacher>Unless the verb is irregular, and we know some irregular verbs already, we saw I am going.

00:01:24.740 --> 00:01:25.380
<v Student>Voy.

00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:25.780
<v Teacher>Voy.

00:01:25.780 --> 00:01:28.100
<v Teacher>So that doesn't end in O or in O.

00:01:28.100 --> 00:01:28.820
<v Teacher>Boi.

00:01:28.820 --> 00:01:30.180
<v Teacher>It's an irregular verb.

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:31.299
<v Teacher>So how does this work?

00:01:31.299 --> 00:01:37.460
<v Teacher>Now, all two verbs, all verbs in their two form, when we say

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:43.520
<v Teacher>To go, to want, to segregate.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:46.080
<v Teacher>How would you say to segregate?

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:50.720
<v Student>Segregation, segregation, segregar.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:51.760
<v Teacher>There you are.

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:56.560
<v Teacher>All of them in the two form end in the letter R.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:58.720
<v Teacher>They either end in AR

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:02.920
<v Teacher>E R or I R.

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:04.440
<v Teacher>We have an example of each.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:11.000
<v Teacher>We have like a thousand examples of the ones that end in AR because this is the rule that we're using to build these from

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:25.560
<v Teacher>For example simulation simulation simular revelation revelation revelar respiration respiracion respirar What do you think respirar means?

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:27.300
<v Teacher>To breathe.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:28.340
<v Teacher>Yes, to breathe.

00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:30.580
<v Teacher>So we could say to respire, really literally.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:39.060
<v Teacher>So we have many examples of our verbs.

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:44.459
<v Teacher>We have one example of an er verb in its true form, which is to know.

00:02:44.459 --> 00:02:45.180
<v Teacher>How was that?

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:46.620
<v Teacher>To know?

00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:47.500
<v Teacher>Saber.

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:48.300
<v Teacher>Saber.

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:53.500
<v Teacher>And we have the example of the verb ending i are, ir, which is to come.

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:54.580
<v Student>Venir.

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:55.940
<v Teacher>Benir, good.

00:02:55.940 --> 00:03:03.860
<v Teacher>So all two forms are gonna end in an R and it's either gonna be R, R or Eir.

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:04.860
<v Teacher>A-R-E-R-I-R.

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:10.460
<v Teacher>In fact, I'm talking about two forms and it's actually with this two that we identify what is a verb.

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:16.700
<v Teacher>Now, it's good to talk about this because at school we learned that verbs are doing words

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:23.600
<v Teacher>Which is really kind of unhelpful because to be, for example, is there's nothing, you're not doing anything.

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:24.640
<v Teacher>If you say is

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:26.220
<v Teacher>He is here.

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:27.260
<v Teacher>What is he doing?

00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:28.460
<v Teacher>But is is a verb?

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:30.700
<v Teacher>Is is a verb because it comes from to be.

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.620
<v Teacher>We don't say he be here.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:34.140
<v Teacher>We say he is here

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:39.580
<v Teacher>So the way we identify what is a verb is that you can put to in front of it.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:41.660
<v Teacher>To be, to stay, to go.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:42.620
<v Teacher>These are verbs.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:47.260
<v Teacher>And in Spanish, these are gonna end in a, either ar, er or ir

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:56.739
<v Teacher>Now the way we get the I version is we take off this ending, we chop off this ar, er, or ear, and we put O.

00:03:56.739 --> 00:03:58.019
<v Teacher>We have an example already.

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:02.660
<v Teacher>We know how is to try, what was to try.

00:04:02.900 --> 00:04:03.940
<v Student>Intentar.

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:04.900
<v Teacher>Intentar.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:05.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:08.020
<v Teacher>And I try.

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:08.900
<v Teacher>Intento.

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:09.700
<v Teacher>Intento.

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:10.020
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:12.340
<v Teacher>So we take off R and we put on O.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.500
<v Teacher>But something else is happening as well.

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:17.220
<v Teacher>Intentar, intento.

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:18.980
<v Teacher>Good, the accent.

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:21.060
<v Teacher>Intentar, we have the accent on the end.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:23.940
<v Teacher>When we put the O, the accent is just before it.

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:24.740
<v Teacher>Intento.

00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:26.100
<v Teacher>Now this is extremely important.

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.380
<v Teacher>If I say intento

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:30.380
<v Teacher>If I put the accent on the end, it means something else.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:31.740
<v Teacher>It means he tried.

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:34.940
<v Teacher>Which is going to be useful for us later when we learn the past.

00:04:34.940 --> 00:04:42.780
<v Teacher>For now, we need to think that the accent in the present tense is going on the penultimate syllable, the second last syllable.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:45.060
<v Teacher>Intentar is not present tense.

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:46.180
<v Teacher>It has no tense.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:48.500
<v Teacher>It's the two form, two try.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:55.060
<v Teacher>Part of the present tense, avan important is also moving the accent.

00:04:55.060 --> 00:04:55.620
<v Teacher>Intento

00:04:56.520 --> 00:04:59.240
<v Teacher>How would you say to donate?

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:02.840
<v Student>Donation, donation, donar.

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:03.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:04.200
<v Teacher>Donar.

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:08.200
<v Teacher>I donate, you take off the R and you put O.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:10.520
<v Teacher>Dono, yes.

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:11.320
<v Teacher>Dono.

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:14.600
<v Teacher>I don't donate or I'm not donating.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:15.640
<v Teacher>No dono.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:16.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:17.480
<v Teacher>No dono.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.120
<v Teacher>How was to create?

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:28.980
<v Teacher>crear good crear creación crear i create creo creo good

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:33.660
<v Teacher>Comer means to eat.

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:36.540
<v Teacher>So how do you say I eat or I'm eating?

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:38.700
<v Student>Como.

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.060
<v Teacher>I'm going to eat.

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:43.920
<v Student>Voya comer.

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:46.320
<v Teacher>Boy a comer.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:49.760
<v Teacher>The word for late in Spanish is tarde

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:50.919
<v Teacher>Tarde.

00:05:50.919 --> 00:05:56.680
<v Teacher>We know this uh from English as well because you have this uh slang in English, in British English at least.

00:05:56.680 --> 00:05:57.479
<v Teacher>Tardi.

00:05:57.479 --> 00:05:58.520
<v Teacher>Have you ever heard that?

00:05:58.520 --> 00:05:58.840
<v Student>Yeah.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:05:59.800
<v Teacher>Tarde.

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:00.840
<v Teacher>Tarde.

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:03.240
<v Teacher>So how would you say I'm going to eat late

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:06.040
<v Student>Voy a comer tarde.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:06.440
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.360
<v Teacher>Voy a comer tarde.

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:12.440
<v Teacher>You might have heard the word for tomorrow as well in Spanish.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:13.400
<v Teacher>Mañana.

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.160
<v Teacher>So how would you say I'm going to eat tomorrow?

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
<v Student>Voy a comer mañana.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.320
<v Teacher>Voy a comer mañana.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:31.360
<v Teacher>Now in Spanish, if you have some kind of future context, something that's showing you that you're talking about the future, you can just use the present.

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:40.419
<v Teacher>You can say voy a comer mañana or you can just say I eat tomorrow because you have tomorrow showing you that you're talking about the future.

00:06:40.419 --> 00:06:43.620
<v Teacher>It's absolutely perfect Spanish, even though it sounds a bit odd in English.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:45.760
<v Teacher>It's perfect Spanish to say I eat tomorrow.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.040
<v Teacher>There's no problem there.

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:48.800
<v Teacher>So how would you say that?

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:51.200
<v Teacher>Como mañana.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:52.560
<v Teacher>Como mañana.

00:06:52.200 --> 00:07:01.400
<v Teacher>So if you wanted to say I'm eating with Pablo tomorrow, I'm eating with Pablo tomorrow, you just say I eat with Pablo tomorrow

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:04.000
<v Student>How do you say with?

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.320
<v Teacher>Do you remember how to say to confirm?

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:09.520
<v Teacher>Confirmacion?

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:10.480
<v Teacher>Confirmar.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.640
<v Teacher>Good, and what did that mean literally?

00:07:12.639 --> 00:07:13.360
<v Teacher>Confirm.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:14.240
<v Student>Ah, with signature.

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:15.280
<v Teacher>Ah, so what is with?

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:16.240
<v Student>Confirma.

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:16.720
<v Student>Con.

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:17.440
<v Teacher>Con.

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:18.080
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:21.040
<v Teacher>So I'm meeting with Pablo tomorrow

00:07:22.360 --> 00:07:25.000
<v Student>Como con Pablo Magana.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:25.560
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:27.560
<v Teacher>Como con Pablo Magnana.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:28.840
<v Teacher>So we can just use the present.

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:33.960
<v Teacher>Or we can say I'm going to eat with Pablo tomorrow and it's a it's the same.

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:38.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:38.520 --> 00:07:41.080
<v Teacher>Boyacomer con Pablo Magnana.

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:42.440
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:52.420
<v Teacher>So we are taking off our ending, we are taking off our, er or ear, and we are adding o to get the I version.

00:07:52.220 --> 00:08:00.460
<v Teacher>We are also accenting the penultimate syllable, the syllable that comes before the last.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.380
<v Teacher>What is to organize?

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:06.800
<v Student>Organization organizar.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:07.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:11.680
<v Teacher>Now how do you say I organize or I'm organizing?

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:13.440
<v Student>Organizo.

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:14.560
<v Teacher>Organizo.

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:15.360
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:24.160
<v Teacher>I will just mention for anybody trying to keep up with the Spanish pronunciation that that Z there is going to be pronounced Th, Organizo in Spain.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:25.360
<v Teacher>Organizo.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:30.680
<v Teacher>To have in Spanish is tener, tener.

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:31.479
<v Student>Tener.

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:33.640
<v Teacher>How do you say I want to have it?

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:34.919
<v Teacher>I want to have it

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:40.760
<v Teacher>Good, I'm going to have it.

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:43.000
<v Student>Voy a tenerlo.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:43.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:45.800
<v Teacher>I'm going to have it late.

00:08:49.279 --> 00:08:51.839
<v Teacher>Cut boy at tenerlo tarde.

00:08:51.839 --> 00:08:53.360
<v Teacher>If you want to say later

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:57.800
<v Teacher>You can say more late and the word for more is mas, M-A-S.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:08:58.440
<v Student>Mas.

00:08:58.440 --> 00:08:59.960
<v Teacher>Related to massive.

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:02.360
<v Teacher>So how is later?

00:09:02.360 --> 00:09:03.720
<v Student>Mas tarde.

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:04.680
<v Teacher>Mass tarde.

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:05.000
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.160
<v Teacher>I'm going to have it later.

00:09:10.699 --> 00:09:11.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:14.139
<v Teacher>I will tell you something that's gonna help you remember tener.

00:09:14.139 --> 00:09:17.500
<v Teacher>Tener is a very interesting verb because other than to have

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:21.300
<v Teacher>We can also translate it as thane.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:23.540
<v Teacher>Contain is contener.

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:26.660
<v Teacher>Obtain, this thane is tener.

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:30.100
<v Teacher>So how would you say obtain in Spanish?

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:33.540
<v Teacher>If contain becomes contener?

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:34.420
<v Teacher>Obtener.

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:35.860
<v Teacher>Yes, obtener.

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:38.340
<v Teacher>Sustain this one changes a little bit.

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:41.460
<v Teacher>SUS which is S U S it becomes SOS.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.600
<v Teacher>in Spanish.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:44.640
<v Teacher>Sostener.

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:45.760
<v Teacher>Sostener.

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:46.960
<v Teacher>Sosten.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:48.000
<v Teacher>Maintain.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:48.640
<v Teacher>Maintain.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.760
<v Teacher>This main becomes man in Spanish.

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:53.760
<v Teacher>So how would you say maintain?

00:09:54.839 --> 00:09:55.880
<v Student>Mantener.

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:56.680
<v Teacher>Mantener.

00:09:56.680 --> 00:10:01.640
<v Teacher>And if you heard entretener, what do would you think it means, entretener?

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:03.260
<v Student>Entertain.

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:03.740
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:07.100
<v Teacher>So it changes a little bit, but you can recognize it.

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:07.980
<v Teacher>Entretener.

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:10.220
<v Teacher>And entre in Spanish means between.

00:10:10.220 --> 00:10:14.380
<v Teacher>You might hear in Spanish, entre tuyo, between you and I.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:16.060
<v Teacher>Entre tuyo.

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:22.040
<v Teacher>Many languages express this idea of possession in different ways.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:26.680
<v Teacher>In English and in Spanish we have a simple verb, have tener to express possession.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:33.860
<v Teacher>Arabic for example, you would say at me or with me instead of I have.

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:36.660
<v Teacher>So it's not a straightforward concept

00:10:36.459 --> 00:10:42.060
<v Teacher>that all languages express in the same way this concept of possession.

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:49.180
<v Teacher>In Turkish, for example, if you want to say I have a car you say my car there is

00:10:49.459 --> 00:10:56.820
<v Teacher>So it's not such a straightforward concept that we are expressing in all languages in the same way, this concept of possession.

00:10:56.820 --> 00:11:03.300
<v Teacher>Something that Spanish is alluding to here is kind of the symbiotic relationship in ownership

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:05.980
<v Teacher>When you own something, you also belong to it.

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:09.900
<v Teacher>You must maintain it, you must sustain it, you must contain it.

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:11.740
<v Teacher>It's a symbiotic relationship.

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:14.860
<v Teacher>You don't just own things, you are also owned by them.

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:19.120
<v Teacher>To have is tener and you also get these other verbs that you can use.

00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:24.320
<v Teacher>Obtener, contener, mantener, sostener, entretener.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.400
<v Teacher>I have is tengo.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:28.680
<v Teacher>What happened here?

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:31.080
<v Teacher>What should it be?

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:31.880
<v Teacher>Tengo.

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:33.160
<v Teacher>Yes, it's what it should be.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:34.600
<v Teacher>But it's irregular

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:35.880
<v Teacher>Has a G popping up.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:39.720
<v Teacher>But the nice thing about the irregular verbs in Spanish is that we can group them together.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:43.080
<v Teacher>There's always a little group of verbs that do things in the same way.

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:45.800
<v Teacher>So for example, what was to come?

00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:47.780
<v Student>Vene vanir.

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:48.340
<v Teacher>Venir.

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:48.660
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:11:48.660 --> 00:11:52.500
<v Teacher>Now venir behaves like tenir when it makes the eye form.

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:56.580
<v Teacher>So if tener becomes tengo, venir might become

00:11:57.980 --> 00:11:58.860
<v Teacher>Vengo.

00:11:58.860 --> 00:11:59.740
<v Teacher>Bengo.

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:00.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:01.980
<v Teacher>So I come is bengo.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:02.940
<v Teacher>It's irregular.

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:07.819
<v Teacher>But we've already noticed two verbs that have the same pattern of irregularity.

00:12:07.819 --> 00:12:10.459
<v Teacher>And to think of them together helps us.

00:12:09.959 --> 00:12:18.120
<v Teacher>Now, if you want to say I will come tomorrow, we don't know the word for will, but we don't need it because tomorrow is our future context.

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:20.120
<v Teacher>What is the word for tomorrow?

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:21.320
<v Student>Maniana.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:21.720
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:24.200
<v Teacher>So I'm coming tomorrow?

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:25.240
<v Student>Vengo manana.

00:12:25.240 --> 00:12:26.440
<v Teacher>Vengo manana.

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:28.200
<v Teacher>Very good.

